---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="AuDHD vs Autism: Key Differences Explained"
  description="How does AuDHD differ from autism alone? Learn the key differences in executive function, social behavior, sensory needs, and daily experience."
  type="article"
>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-12">
    <header class="mb-10">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-text">AuDHD vs Autism: What Changes When ADHD Enters the Picture</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-text-light leading-relaxed">
        Autism and AuDHD share a foundation, but they don't feel the same to live with. Adding ADHD to autism doesn't just add a few extra traits on top. It fundamentally changes how autism shows up. Here's where the two diverge.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Routine: Love It vs. Love-Hate It</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Autistic people typically find comfort and stability in routines. Once a good routine is established, sticking with it feels natural. Disruptions cause stress, and the routine itself provides a sense of control in an unpredictable world.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          AuDHD flips this. You still <em>need</em> routine for the same reasons, but the ADHD component rebels against repetition. Monday's perfect morning routine feels like a prison by Wednesday. So you redesign it. Again. And again. AuDHD people often cycle through productivity systems, planners, and habit trackers at a rate that would give a minimalist a headache. The need for structure is autistic. The inability to maintain it is ADHD.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Special Interests vs. Hyperfixations</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Autistic special interests tend to be deep and long-lasting. Someone might spend years, even a lifetime, building expertise in trains, marine biology, or a specific video game franchise. The interest persists.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          In AuDHD, special interests still happen, but they collide with ADHD's hyperfixation pattern. You discover something new and throw yourself into it with the intensity of an autistic special interest, only to have the ADHD novelty-seeking kick in after three weeks. You're left with 12 abandoned hobbies, a garage full of equipment, and a lingering sense of shame. Some interests do stick long-term. But the turnover rate is much higher than in autism alone.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Social Interaction Looks Different</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Autistic people without ADHD often present as quiet, reserved, or selectively social. They may prefer one-on-one conversations, need significant alone time, and avoid small talk. Social difficulty tends to show up as withdrawal or awkwardness.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          AuDHD social presentation is messier. The ADHD impulsivity means you might be the <em>opposite</em> of quiet. You talk too much, interrupt without meaning to, info-dump about your current obsession, and then spend the entire drive home agonizing over every word you said. Socially, AuDHD can look extroverted on the surface while the internal experience is pure overwhelm. Clinicians sometimes miss the autism entirely because "you're too social to be autistic." Wrong. You're too ADHD to <em>look</em> autistic.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Executive Function Breakdown</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Both autism and AuDHD involve executive function challenges, but the flavor is different. Autistic executive function difficulties often center on cognitive flexibility: trouble switching tasks, difficulty adapting to change, challenges with open-ended planning.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          AuDHD stacks initiation problems on top. You can't switch tasks <em>and</em> you can't start them. Planning requires flexibility you don't have, but starting the plan requires activation energy you also don't have. The result is a particular kind of paralysis that autism alone doesn't produce. You know what to do, you've planned it meticulously, and you're sitting on the couch unable to begin.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Sensory Processing: Predictable vs. Contradictory</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Autistic sensory profiles tend to be relatively consistent. If you're noise-sensitive, you're generally noise-sensitive. You learn your triggers and can plan around them.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          AuDHD sensory needs shift depending on your current state. Understimulated? You crank up the music, seek out crunchy textures, take a scalding shower. Overstimulated? That same music makes you want to scream. Your sensory profile changes based on whether the ADHD brain is seeking stimulation or the autistic brain is in overload. Predicting your own needs becomes a guessing game, even after years of self-awareness.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text mb-4">Masking Gets Layered</h2>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed">
          Autistic masking is already exhausting. Scripting responses, monitoring body language, suppressing stims. AuDHD adds a second mask on top: hiding impulsivity, pretending you were listening, covering up the fact that you forgot something important (again). Two masks running simultaneously means burnout hits faster, harder, and more often.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mt-3">
          One practical takeaway: if you've been diagnosed with autism but standard autistic coping strategies only partially work, the missing piece might be undiagnosed ADHD.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 bg-accent/10 rounded-[--radius-xl] p-6 sm:p-8">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-text mb-3">Explore More</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2">
        <li><a href="/quiz/autism-or-adhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">Autism, ADHD, or Both? Take the quiz &rarr;</a></li>
        <li><a href="/learn/audhd-vs-adhd/" class="text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors">AuDHD vs ADHD: how they differ &rarr;</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
